=========================================================
LAMBDA THREAD (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition
----------

A lambda expression can be used directly as the thread function.

Useful for short tasks without creating a separate function.

---------------------------------------------------------

Syntax

thread t([]()
{
    // Thread code
});

---------------------------------------------------------

Example

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    thread t([]()
    {
        cout << "Hello from Lambda Thread\n";
    });

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

Output

Hello from Lambda Thread

---------------------------------------------------------

Lambda with Arguments (Capture)

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 10;

    thread t([x]()
    {
        cout << "Value = " << x << endl;
    });

    t.join();

    return 0;
}

Output

Value = 10

---------------------------------------------------------

Capture by Reference

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 10;

    thread t([&x]()
    {
        x++;
    });

    t.join();

    cout << x << endl;
}

Output

11

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Points

✓ Ideal for small thread tasks.
✓ No separate function is required.
✓ Supports variable capture by value ([x]) and by reference ([&x]).
✓ Improves code readability for short operations.

---------------------------------------------------------

One-line Interview Answer

"A lambda thread uses a lambda expression as the thread function, making it convenient for short, self-contained tasks."

---------------------------------------------------------

Memory Trick

Normal Thread

thread t(print);

↓

Lambda Thread

thread t([]()
{
    // Task
});
